The Aeneid.

The Aeneid is the great epic of Rome. It was founded on the two epics of Homer, ‘the Iliad and the Odyssey, and is at once a sequel to the former and a companion to the latter. The poem describes the wanderings of Aeneas, from whom Rome sprang, and conducts him from Troy to his final settlement in Italy. The whole tale shortly is as follows.

Paris, son of Priam. king of Troy, was a shepherd feeding his flocks on Mount Ida. To him came the goddesses, Venus, Juno, Minerva (we use the Latin names) to decide who was the fairest. Paris gave his decision in favour of Venus, who bribed him by the offer of—

‘The fairest and most loving bride in Greece:

This bride was Helen, wife of Menelaus, king of Sparta.

who fied with Paris to Troy. The Greeks fitted out a. large expedition under the command of Agamemnon, brother of Menelaus, and for ten years Troy was besieged. Hector on the Trojan side, Achilles, Ajax, Ulysses, Diomedes, &c. on the Grecian,were the chief combatants, but the city did not fall until there was devised the stratagem of the wooden horse, described in Aeneid ii.
